Electromagnetic Induction

What is Induced e.m.f.?

(Tap to reveal)

  • An electromotive force (e.m.f.) is induced in a conductor when there is relative movement between the conductor and a magnetic field.
  • This happens in two ways:
    1. The conductor moves in a stationary magnetic field.
    2. The conductor is stationary in a changing magnetic field.
  • Essentially, an e.m.f. is induced when the conductor cuts magnetic field lines.

Demonstrating Induction

(Tap to reveal)

  • To demonstrate, move a bar magnet into a coil of wire connected to a galvanometer.
  • Moving magnet IN: Galvanometer deflects one way.
  • Moving magnet OUT: Galvanometer deflects the opposite way.
  • Holding magnet STILL: No deflection. No cutting of field lines means no induced e.m.f.
  • Reversing the magnet's pole and repeating the steps will reverse the direction of the deflection.

Fleming's Right-Hand Rule

(Tap to reveal)

  • Used to find the direction of induced current in a generator.
  • Thumb = Thrust / Motion
  • Forefinger = Field (North to South)
  • Centre finger = Current (Induced)
  • *Refer to the diagram illustrating Fleming's Right-Hand Rule.*

Factors Affecting Induced e.m.f.

To increase the size of the induced e.m.f., you can:

  • Increase the speed of the relative motion between the coil and the magnet.
  • Increase the number of turns on the coil.
  • Increase the strength of the magnetic field (use a stronger magnet).

The A.C. Generator

What is an A.C. Generator?

(Tap to reveal)

  • Its function is to convert kinetic energy into electrical energy.
  • It consists of a rectangular coil of wire that is forced to rotate in a magnetic field.
  • Key components: Coil, Magnetic Field, Slip Rings, and Carbon Brushes.
  • *Refer to the diagram of an A.C. generator.*

How does it work?

(Tap to reveal)

  • As the coil rotates, the sides of the coil cut through the magnetic field lines.
  • This induces an e.m.f. in the coil (using Fleming's Right-Hand Rule), which drives a current.
  • The slip rings make continuous contact between the rotating coil and the stationary carbon brushes.
  • The direction of the induced current reverses every half rotation, producing an alternating current (A.C.).

Generator Output

(Tap to reveal)

  • The output e.m.f. varies in a sinusoidal pattern.
  • Maximum e.m.f.: When the coil is horizontal, its sides move fastest through the field lines.
  • Zero e.m.f.: When the coil is vertical, its sides move parallel to the field lines and do not cut them.
  • *Refer to the graph of output voltage vs. time for an A.C. generator.*

Factors Affecting Output

The magnitude of the induced e.m.f. can be increased by:

  • Increasing the speed of rotation of the coil.
  • Increasing the number of turns on the coil.
  • Increasing the strength of the magnetic field.
  • Increasing the area of the coil.
  • Inserting a soft iron core inside the coil to concentrate the field lines.

Magnetic Effect of a Current

Field around a Straight Wire

(Tap to reveal)

  • When a current flows through a wire, it produces a magnetic field around it.
  • The field lines are a series of concentric circles centered on the wire.
  • The direction of the field can be found using the Right-Hand Grip Rule: Point thumb in current direction, fingers curl in field direction.
  • *Refer to the diagram showing the field lines.*

Field around a Solenoid

(Tap to reveal)

  • A solenoid is a long coil of wire.
  • The magnetic field inside a current-carrying solenoid is strong and uniform.
  • Outside the solenoid, the field is similar to that of a bar magnet, with a North and South pole.
  • You can find the North pole using the Right-Hand Grip Rule: Curl fingers in the direction of current, thumb points to the North pole.

Strengthening an Electromagnet

You can make the magnetic field of a solenoid (an electromagnet) stronger by:

  • Increasing the current in the coil.
  • Increasing the number of turns on the coil.
  • Placing a soft iron core inside the solenoid.

Force on a Current-Carrying Conductor

The Motor Effect

(Tap to reveal)

  • The motor effect describes how a current-carrying wire placed in a magnetic field experiences a force.
  • This happens because the magnetic field of the wire interacts with the external magnetic field.
  • The force is greatest when the wire is perpendicular (90¬∞) to the magnetic field lines.
  • There is no force if the wire is parallel to the field lines.

Fleming's Left-Hand Rule

(Tap to reveal)

  • This rule is used to find the direction of the force (or motion).
  • Thumb = Thrust / Force
  • Forefinger = Field (North to South)
  • Centre finger = Current (+ to -)
  • *Refer to the diagram illustrating Fleming's Left-Hand Rule.*

Factors Affecting the Force

The size of the force can be increased by:

  • Increasing the current.
  • Using a stronger magnetic field.
  • Increasing the length of the wire within the magnetic field.

Calculating the Force (Extended)

The magnitude of the force is given by the equation:

F = B × I × L
  • F = Force in Newtons (N)
  • B = Magnetic flux density (a measure of field strength) in Tesla (T)
  • I = Current in Amperes (A)
  • L = Length of wire in the field in metres (m)

Electric Motors

What is an Electric Motor?

(Tap to reveal)

  • Its function is to convert electrical energy into kinetic energy.
  • It uses the motor effect to create continuous rotation.
  • Key components: Coil, Magnetic Field, Split-Ring Commutator, and Carbon Brushes.
  • *Refer to the diagram of a D.C. electric motor.*

How does it work?

(Tap to reveal)

  • Current flows through the coil. The current on the two sides of the coil flows in opposite directions.
  • Using Fleming's Left-Hand Rule, one side of the coil is forced up, and the other side is forced down.
  • This pair of forces creates a turning effect (moment), causing the coil to rotate.

The Split-Ring Commutator

(Tap to reveal)

  • This is the crucial component for continuous rotation!
  • Its purpose is to reverse the direction of the current in the coil every half turn.
  • This ensures the force on each side of the coil always acts in the same turning direction (e.g., left side always pushed up, right side always pushed down), keeping the motor spinning.

Making the Motor Faster

The speed of rotation can be increased by:

  • Increasing the current.
  • Increasing the number of turns on the coil.
  • Increasing the strength of the magnetic field.
  • Placing a soft iron core inside the coil.

Transformers

What is a Transformer?

(Tap to reveal)

  • A device used to change the voltage of an alternating current (A.C.).
  • Consists of two coils, a primary coil and a secondary coil, wrapped around a continuous soft iron core.
  • IMPORTANT: Transformers do not work with direct current (D.C.).

How does it work?

(Tap to reveal)

  • An A.C. supply to the primary coil creates a continuously changing magnetic field in the iron core.
  • The soft iron core concentrates and guides this changing magnetic field through the secondary coil.
  • This changing magnetic field induces an alternating e.m.f. across the secondary coil.

Power Transmission

(Tap to reveal)

  • Electricity is transmitted over long distances at very high voltages and low currents.
  • Why? To reduce power loss in the transmission cables.
  • Power lost as heat is calculated by: P = I2R
  • By making the current (I) very small, the power loss is significantly reduced.
  • A step-up transformer is used at the power station, and a step-down transformer is used near homes.

Step-Up vs. Step-Down

Step-Up Transformer

  • Increases voltage.
  • More turns on secondary coil than primary (Ns > Np).

Step-Down Transformer

  • Decreases voltage.
  • Fewer turns on secondary coil than primary (Ns < Np).

Transformer Calculations

The ratio of voltages is equal to the ratio of the number of turns:

Vs⁄Vp = Ns⁄Np

For a 100% efficient transformer, power in = power out:

Vp × Ip = Vs × Is

Note: Real transformers are highly efficient (>99%) but some energy is always lost as heat and sound.
